#Text=Grytviken
#Text=Grytviken is the whaling station made famous by Shackleton 's reunion with civilization on South Georgia after losing his ship , the Endurance , to Antarctic pack ice in 1915 .
#Text=Toast " Bring ' em Back Shack " at his gravesite in a small cemetery overlooking the bay .
#Text=Although the grave of Ernest Shackleton can be found in the little graveyard here , Grytviken is not the whaling station where he finally found help after his epic journey .
#Text=This was at the nearby Stromness whaling station .
#Text=Get in
#Text=The usual way to arrive is by boat .
#Text=Get around
#Text=You can easily walk around the settlement .
#Text=See
#Text=The abandoned whaling station has undergone a project to remove all asbestos and dangerous collapsing buildings and may be explored .
#Text=The station was active in the whaling industry until the middle of the last century .
#Text=Other popular visitor destinations include the restored Norwegian church , and the cemetery , which contains the grave of the famous explorer Ernest Shackleton .
#Text=The British Antarctic Survey maintains a presence on the island in a recently renovated research station on nearby King Edward Point .
#Text=Do
#Text=South Georgia Museum .
#Text=October-March .
#Text=The museum was established in 1991 and operates in the former whaling station manager 's house .
#Text=Today it is managed by the South Georgia Heritage Trust and provide exhibits about the exploration , whaling and natural history of the island .
#Text=Most ships visiting the island stop in Grytviken , and the museum is well worth an hour or two of your time .
#Text=The museum also provides the unique opportunity to talk to staff members about what it is like to spend extended periods living on a remote , sub-Antarctic island .
#Text=Hike up to the reservoir .
#Text=Located on the hill above the whaling station is a fairly large lake .
#Text=Footing may be muddy , but the scenery is nice and the view of the bay is excellent .
#Text=Be aware that terns may begin attacking from the air ; if they do it means that you are near their nest and should backtrack until they feel you are a safe distance away .
#Text=Visit Shackleton 's grave .
#Text=The cemetery is on the opposite side of the whaling station from the museum .
#Text=Shackleton is buried here along with many of the whalers who died on South Georgia .
#Text=Visit Shackleton 's cross , at the end of King Edward Point , beyond the British Base .
#Text=A trail to the cross is fairly easy to follow .

#Text=While visiting , be on the lookout for the very territorial fur seals ; should one charge you , it is best to carry a long stick or tripod with which to tickle its whiskers , which surprisingly deters most attacks .
#Text=Write letters home .
#Text=There is a mailbox in front of the museum , and stamps and postcards can be purchased in the gift shop .
#Text=Mail will reach most destinations within two or three weeks .
#Text=According to a recent program on BBC Radio 4 , the ashes of Frank Wild , Shackleton 's right hand man , have been placed alongside Shackleton 's grave .
#Text=Frank Wild was in charge of the men left on Elephant Island for months whilst Shackleton went for help .
#Text=Buy
#Text=There is a small gift shop in the museum that sells books of local interest , posters , and sundry other souvenirs .
#Text=British pounds , Falklands pounds , Euros , and American dollars will all be accepted , as will Visa and Mastercard ( but not AMEX ) .
#Text=The Post Office is open upon request 1km away at King Edward Point and may be brought on board larger ships .
#Text=The Post Office has a range of postcards , stamps , first day covers , South Georgia coins and a few South Georgia Government publications for sale .
#Text=Eat
#Text=You will need to bring your own food .
#Text=Go next
#Text=King Edward Point .
#Text=Located a short walk along the harbour from the whaling station .
